he U.S. comic book industry. Among the explorations of mainstream and independent comic books are discussions of the work of Adrian Tomine, Grant Morrison, and Jessica Abel as well as Marv Wolfman and Gene Colan's The Tomb of Dracula; Native American Anishinaabe-related comics; mixed-media forms such as Kerry James Marshall's comic-book/community performance; DJ Spooky's visual remix of classic film; the role of comics in India; and race in the early Underground Comix movement. The collection includes a "one-stop shop" for multicultural comic book resources, such as archives, websites, and scholarly books. Each of the essays shows in a systematic, clear, and precise way how multicultural comic books work in and of themselves and also how they are interconnected with a worldwide tradition of comic-book storytelling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comics & Graphic Novels.2bisacsh1 aAldama, Frederick Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAldama, Frederick Luis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGardner, Jared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Patrick L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHetrick, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJesús, Melinda L. de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMehta, Suhaan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNixon, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoori, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, James Braxton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRifas, Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v